relative is diagnosed at a young age.

540
00:32:12.560 --> 00:32:16.520
Historically, prior GWAS have focused mainly on smoking-related lung cancer,

541
00:32:16.600 --> 00:32:20.520
which is the most common type of lung cancer, and have identified

542
00:32:20.540 --> 00:32:22.380
loci that mediate smoking behavior.

543
00:32:23.200 --> 00:32:26.940
And in contrast, GWAS from never smokers have

544
00:32:26.980 --> 00:32:30.280
not converged in the same way on a robust set of

545
00:32:30.340 --> 00:32:32.060
associations and tend to,

546
00:32:32.920 --> 00:32:36.340
generally speaking, consider European and Asian

547
00:32:36.360 --> 00:32:37.560
populations separately.

548
00:32:38.460 --> 00:32:42.440
And although rare variant and familial studies have pointed to genes

549
00:32:42.500 --> 00:32:46.460
like ATM and BRCA and EGFR, we

550
00:32:46.499 --> 00:32:50.280
don't totally understand the genetic architecture of risk in

551
00:32:50.340 --> 00:32:51.640
non-smoking lung cancer.

552
00:32:53.040 --> 00:32:56.420
So this is a conceptual model that we have proposed where

553
00:32:56.840 --> 00:33:00.780
germline variation interacts with environmental exposures and somatic

554
00:33:00.820 --> 00:33:04.740
alterations to ultimately influence lung cancer development in those who have

555
00:33:04.800 --> 00:33:08.700
not smoked. So starting on the left, you have germline

556
00:33:08.760 --> 00:33:11.260
variation, which exists across the spectrum.

557
00:33:11.500 --> 00:33:14.870
There's common variants, individually, each with small effect sizes.

558
00:33:15.520 --> 00:33:19.140
Examples of this are polygenic risk scores that are comprised of

559
00:33:19.200 --> 00:33:23.150
SNPs identified in GWAS. And then on the other end

560
00:33:23.180 --> 00:33:26.900
of the spectrum, you have your rare and ultra-rare variants with much

561
00:33:26.920 --> 00:33:30.260
larger effect sizes. And examples of this are

562
00:33:30.600 --> 00:33:31.940
pathogenic germline

563
00:33:32.980 --> 00:33:36.520
mutations in TP53, BRCA2, or ATM.

564
00:33:37.260 --> 00:33:41.200
And this germline variation can then affect processes such

565
00:33:41.260 --> 00:33:44.569
as DNA repair, carcinogen metabolism, and

566
00:33:44.620 --> 00:33:48.520
inflammation. And this can be reflected then at the somatic level, where

567
00:33:48.560 --> 00:33:52.320
you can have inactivation of tumor suppressors and activations of

568
00:33:52.380 --> 00:33:54.180
oncogenes. And then on the right,

569
00:33:55.020 --> 00:33:58.500
all of this, in part, can shape tumor biology, including

570
00:33:58.580 --> 00:34:02.240
ultimately selection of drivers, presence of co-mutations,

571
00:34:02.720 --> 00:34:04.440
and interaction with the microenvironment.

572
00:34:04.880 --> 00:34:07.480
And then you have the actual environment, the

573
00:34:07.800 --> 00:34:11.520
exposome, that can interact

574
00:34:11.920 --> 00:34:15.761
at all levels with the germline and somatic genome and

575
00:34:15.801 --> 00:34:19.000
ultimately influence tumor biology.

576
00:34:19.009 --> 00:34:22.220
And so rather than acting in isolation, we think these things are all

577
00:34:22.460 --> 00:34:26.000
interconnected. And this raises the question of how inherited

578
00:34:26.020 --> 00:34:29.861
variation shapes not just risk, but the specific tumor

579
00:34:29.900 --> 00:34:33.880
subtype that develops from a histologic and molecular standpoint.

580
00:34:35.220 --> 00:34:38.781
So one way to approach this is to focus on populations that we think are

581
00:34:38.801 --> 00:34:40.700
enriched for inherited susceptibility.

582
00:34:41.460 --> 00:34:45.301
And in particular, I have focused on three groups that are comprised of mostly

583
00:34:45.341 --> 00:34:48.850
non-smoking disease, the first two of which I will focus on

584
00:34:48.920 --> 00:34:52.750
today. The first is patients with young onset disease, and

585
00:34:52.841 --> 00:34:56.420
for these purposes, that's defined as diagnosed at 45

586
00:34:57.020 --> 00:34:57.459
or younger.

587
00:34:58.290 --> 00:35:02.060
The second are individuals with family histories of lung cancer or personal

588
00:35:02.100 --> 00:35:05.980
histories of other cancers, including multiple cancers over a lifetime.

589
00:35:06.720 --> 00:35:09.890
And then the third are tumors defined by specific drivers,

590
00:35:10.280 --> 00:35:12.360
prototypically EGFR mutant lung cancer.

591
00:35:13.120 --> 00:35:16.650
And importantly, these groups are not mutually exclusive, and in fact, the areas

592
00:35:16.700 --> 00:35:20.660
where they overlap may be the groups that have actually the

593
00:35:20.720 --> 00:35:23.650
most strong germline contributions to risk.

594
00:35:25.450 --> 00:35:29.370
So to study these groups, we developed two correlative research studies that

595
00:35:29.420 --> 00:35:33.190
recruit patients nationwide. The first is called the Biology of Young Lung

596
00:35:33.260 --> 00:35:36.820
Cancer or Young Lung Cancer study, and this is focusing on people

597
00:35:36.880 --> 00:35:40.720
diagnosed at 45 or younger. The second is called INHERIT, or

598
00:35:40.800 --> 00:35:43.660
Investigating Hereditary Risk in Thoracic Cancers.

599
00:35:44.209 --> 00:35:47.500
This focuses on individuals with familial risk, and we are running this in

600
00:35:47.580 --> 00:35:49.520
partnership with GO2 for Lung Cancer.

601
00:35:50.280 --> 00:35:54.040
And both studies are coordinated through Dana-Farber, but recruit nationally with

602
00:35:54.140 --> 00:35:58.130
remote sample collection. Sequencing is performed at the Broad Institute, and

603
00:35:58.180 --> 00:36:00.820
then analysis is performed by our group.

604
00:36:02.020 --> 00:36:05.800
So to enable national recruitment, both studies enroll remotely through study

605
00:36:05.860 --> 00:36:09.600
websites and online platforms. People can enroll from anywhere in the

606
00:36:09.700 --> 00:36:13.380
US, and this allows us to reach groups that otherwise would be difficult to

607
00:36:13.440 --> 00:36:17.340
capture at a single center, particularly for rare subgroups like young

608
00:36:17.400 --> 00:36:19.820
onset lung cancer and familial lung cancer.

609
00:36:20.960 --> 00:36:24.920
And this really enables us to build these cohorts at scale for the genomic analyses

610
00:36:24.960 --> 00:36:25.720
that we want to do.

611
00:36:26.660 --> 00:36:30.560
So it might be helpful to understand the types of data and samples that we

612
00:36:30.620 --> 00:36:31.400
are collecting.

613
00:36:32.240 --> 00:36:35.220
At the time of consent, people enroll remotely.

614
00:36:35.400 --> 00:36:38.880
There's in-home phlebotomy for them to provide a research blood sample

615
00:36:39.380 --> 00:36:43.320
for germline whole genome and RNA sequencing and serum

616
00:36:43.360 --> 00:36:47.356
for banking.They also complete detailed exposure and medical

617
00:36:47.396 --> 00:36:48.976
and family history questionnaires.

618
00:36:49.836 --> 00:36:53.616
These include detailed residential histories, so kind of tracking where people have

619
00:36:53.716 --> 00:36:57.536
lived over the course of their lives, and also occupational

620
00:36:57.576 --> 00:37:00.036
history as well, and then access to medical

621
00:37:00.096 --> 00:37:04.006
records. The optional items, there are optional items.

622
00:37:04.076 --> 00:37:07.276
The first one is clinical germline multigene panel testing.

623
00:37:07.776 --> 00:37:11.596
So this is run through our commercial partner, Invitae, and it's a bespoke

624
00:37:11.696 --> 00:37:15.536
assay consisting of 156 genes across cancer types

625
00:37:15.916 --> 00:37:19.816
made for the study. And there is pre- and post-test genetic counseling

626
00:37:19.856 --> 00:37:23.716
that comes with this, and then for people who are found to have pathogenic germline

627
00:37:23.736 --> 00:37:27.636
variants, there's cascade testing available for family members if they want it.

628
00:37:28.636 --> 00:37:32.096
Second is access to tumor specimens, which is optional, but most people actually do

629
00:37:32.156 --> 00:37:36.076
consent to this, and then serial blood collection every six to 12 months

630
00:37:36.136 --> 00:37:38.056
for banking and future study.

631
00:37:39.856 --> 00:37:42.416
So turning to young onset lung cancer, it's relatively rare.

632
00:37:42.696 --> 00:37:45.716
It makes up about 1% to 2% of overall lung cancer.

633
00:37:46.256 --> 00:37:49.975
Mostly occurs in people who have never smoked and highly enriched for targetable

634
00:37:50.036 --> 00:37:53.156
alterations. Somewhere upwards of 90% will have one.

635
00:37:53.816 --> 00:37:57.386
There's not any unifying exposure or genetic risk factors identified,

636
00:37:57.636 --> 00:38:00.716
and in the past, it's been hard to study because there just aren't that many

637
00:38:00.756 --> 00:38:01.216
patients.

638
00:38:02.356 --> 00:38:06.196
So taking a deeper dive into the somatic data, we looked at the AACR

639
00:38:06.276 --> 00:38:10.116
Project Genie database at over 7,000 lung adenocarcinomas,

640
00:38:10.656 --> 00:38:14.296
and we saw that younger patients did indeed show enrichment for certain targetable

641
00:38:14.356 --> 00:38:17.916
alterations. Most notably, ALK and ROS1

642
00:38:18.016 --> 00:38:21.616
fusions. Those have asterisks next to them on the x-axis.

643
00:38:22.076 --> 00:38:25.736
And then also to a lesser extent, but still, EGFR

644
00:38:25.756 --> 00:38:27.756
mutations associated with younger age.

645
00:38:28.216 --> 00:38:31.816
And then when you look at all fusions grouped together, all fusions

646
00:38:32.416 --> 00:38:36.256
represented in this figure, you can see that there is even

647
00:38:36.316 --> 00:38:39.796
stronger and more significant enrichment for younger onset

648
00:38:39.836 --> 00:38:43.636
disease. And this is in contrast to KRAS mutant lung cancer, which we

649
00:38:43.676 --> 00:38:47.516
found was associated with older patients, which is not surprising given that we

650
00:38:47.536 --> 00:38:51.316
know it's associated with mostly smoking-related disease.

651
00:38:51.376 --> 00:38:54.935
So turning back to the study, we assembled a cohort of young onset patients for

652
00:38:55.036 --> 00:38:56.456
germline whole genome sequencing.

653
00:38:56.836 --> 00:39:00.336
And as I mentioned, these are people 45 or younger at the time of diagnosis,

654
00:39:00.796 --> 00:39:03.596
and it's non-small cell and small cell lung cancer patients.

655
00:39:04.116 --> 00:39:07.546
The cohort was mainly non-small cell, but we did certainly

656
00:39:08.536 --> 00:39:11.536
see some small cell lung cancer cases.

657
00:39:11.546 --> 00:39:15.336
So to date, this cohort includes 620 patients with young onset lung

658
00:39:15.396 --> 00:39:15.816
cancer.

659
00:39:16.716 --> 00:39:20.336
It is predominantly female, adenocarcinoma histology,

660
00:39:21.596 --> 00:39:25.236
stage IV disease, and never or light smoking history.

661
00:39:25.656 --> 00:39:29.316
So 87% of the cohort have five pack years or less.

662
00:39:29.916 --> 00:39:33.556
And then on the bottom here, this is the landscape of

663
00:39:33.776 --> 00:39:37.596
somatic alterations. You can see it's mostly ALK fusions and EGFR

664
00:39:37.606 --> 00:39:41.336
mutations, kind of a smattering of other known drivers, and then a

665
00:39:41.416 --> 00:39:41.716
group

666
00:39:42.556 --> 00:39:45.956
with unknown drivers. And then on the right, this is a map of

667
00:39:45.996 --> 00:39:49.176
participation, so where people reside at the time that they enroll.

668
00:39:49.656 --> 00:39:53.576
So we did have pretty representative participation across the US,

669
00:39:53.656 --> 00:39:56.216
with participants from nearly every state.

670
00:39:59.876 --> 00:40:03.616
So looking at some of the data from this cohort, we performed germline whole

671
00:40:03.686 --> 00:40:07.236
genome sequencing at a data freeze of 251

672
00:40:07.276 --> 00:40:10.966
samples. Median age of

673
00:40:11.036 --> 00:40:14.336
onset was 37, and we analyzed these data

674
00:40:14.376 --> 00:40:18.036
jointly with raw data from 196

675
00:40:18.176 --> 00:40:21.756
never-smoking lung adenocarcinoma cases from the Sherlock Lung

676
00:40:21.896 --> 00:40:25.776
Study. These were published as part of a tumor normal

677
00:40:26.176 --> 00:40:27.866
whole genome study in 2021.

678
00:40:28.916 --> 00:40:32.576
And we analyzed these populations alongside roughly

679
00:40:32.616 --> 00:40:35.816
1,800 cancer-free controls from the TOPMed database.

680
00:40:36.856 --> 00:40:40.556
So, in terms of what we analyzed, we looked at short and structural variants,

681
00:40:40.736 --> 00:40:43.996
structural variants being 50 base pairs or greater in size.

682
00:40:44.756 --> 00:40:48.656
And this included common variants that compose polygenic risk scores and then

683
00:40:48.696 --> 00:40:52.496
rare coding variants in gene and gene set based

684
00:40:52.516 --> 00:40:56.476
burden testing. And we then correlated this burden with clinicopathological

685
00:40:56.516 --> 00:41:00.146
information such as survival and smoking status, as well as

686
00:41:00.176 --> 00:41:03.696
somatic data. And we can see in Panel B, so we

687
00:41:03.736 --> 00:41:07.656
captured a fairly wide spectrum of variation among short and

688
00:41:07.696 --> 00:41:08.756
structural variants.

689
00:41:09.696 --> 00:41:13.176
In Panel C, in terms of ancestry, the population was largely

690
00:41:13.216 --> 00:41:16.456
European, about 85%, and these were the

691
00:41:17.136 --> 00:41:19.376
samples that we used in our downstream analysis.

692
00:41:20.756 --> 00:41:24.196
And then in this last panel, we calculated polygenic risk scores

693
00:41:24.276 --> 00:41:27.516
study-wide based on a recent cross-ancestry

694
00:41:27.956 --> 00:41:31.516
GWAS meta-analysis of over 60,000 lung cancer

695
00:41:31.616 --> 00:41:35.276
cases. And what you can see here is that in both cancer

696
00:41:35.336 --> 00:41:37.096
sample sets, the young onset

697
00:41:38.076 --> 00:41:41.896
patients and the never-smoking patients compared to controls, the

698
00:41:41.916 --> 00:41:45.856
polygenic risk scores for lung adenocarcinoma were associated with a

699
00:41:45.896 --> 00:41:49.836
small amount of risk. The odds ratios were in the 1.3 range per

700
00:41:49.856 --> 00:41:51.856
standard deviation increase in PRS.

701
00:41:52.876 --> 00:41:56.046
And this was interesting to us, given that this PRS was derived mainly from

702
00:41:56.096 --> 00:42:00.016
smoking-associated lung cancer, and it suggests that some component of inherited

703
00:42:00.116 --> 00:42:03.976
risk may be shared across smoking and non-smoking disease.

704
00:42:05.676 --> 00:42:09.176
So to increase power in this relatively modest sample size, we

705
00:42:09.296 --> 00:42:12.956
aggregated variants at the level of biologically defined

706
00:42:13.096 --> 00:42:16.936
gene sets and pathways. And so these were pathways a

707
00:42:16.996 --> 00:42:20.756
priori that are known to be involved in either lung cancer biology or cancer

708
00:42:20.836 --> 00:42:24.756
biology in general. And out of 146 gene sets

709
00:42:24.796 --> 00:42:28.656
that we tested among young onset cases, we saw enrichment for

710
00:42:28.696 --> 00:42:32.046
rare pathogenic variation across 55 of those

711
00:42:32.056 --> 00:42:35.856
cancer-associated gene sets. And these are the top

712
00:42:35.916 --> 00:42:38.436
hits here. These were the most significant.

713
00:42:39.596 --> 00:42:42.356
And they included TP53 as a single gene.

714
00:42:42.576 --> 00:42:46.476
That was the only gene set that we composed of a single gene, more for

715
00:42:46.556 --> 00:42:50.176
positive control, but we were really surprised to see the degree of

716
00:42:50.196 --> 00:42:53.906
enrichment among the young onset cases compared to the non-smoking cases,

717
00:42:54.716 --> 00:42:58.674
and also the effect sizes were quite large.And then the other pathways

718
00:42:58.724 --> 00:43:02.344
we saw enrichment were signaling pathways involved in non-small cell lung cancer,

719
00:43:02.804 --> 00:43:06.604
tumor suppressor gene sets, the clinical panel from Invitae that I

720
00:43:06.724 --> 00:43:10.604
mentioned earlier, and then some pediatric and adult cancer

721
00:43:10.664 --> 00:43:13.704
gene sets as well. And if you look on the x-axis,

722
00:43:14.244 --> 00:43:17.964
across the x-axis, we're varying how stringently

723
00:43:18.644 --> 00:43:22.364
we define damaging variants. So CV is ClinVar pathogenic variants,

724
00:43:22.744 --> 00:43:25.624
and then as you move to the right, there are more inclusive definitions

725
00:43:25.664 --> 00:43:27.844
incorporating predicted functional impact.

726
00:43:28.284 --> 00:43:31.084
Then the categories become less stringent from left to right.

727
00:43:32.024 --> 00:43:35.984
So overall, this suggests that rare pathogenic germline

728
00:43:36.024 --> 00:43:39.904
variation in established cancer genes contributes to risk in young onset

729
00:43:39.964 --> 00:43:40.604
lung cancer.

730
00:43:42.824 --> 00:43:46.564
So having seen enrichment at the level of the gene sets, we asked whether there

731
00:43:46.574 --> 00:43:49.244
were specific genes driving these signals.

732
00:43:50.124 --> 00:43:53.884
To do this, we performed an exome-wide rare variant association

733
00:43:53.944 --> 00:43:56.704
test across roughly 19,000 genes.

734
00:43:57.174 --> 00:44:01.084
And these are QQ plots that show results on the left for all lung cancers

735
00:44:01.444 --> 00:44:05.284
and then non-fusion driven lung cancers, and then fusion driven lung

736
00:44:05.384 --> 00:44:05.824
cancers.

737
00:44:07.444 --> 00:44:11.014
And what you can see is that we see clear deviation from expectation with

738
00:44:11.044 --> 00:44:14.864
TP53, again, emerging as the strongest signal among all lung

739
00:44:14.964 --> 00:44:18.864
cancers. But then when we stratified by tumor subtype, so

740
00:44:18.964 --> 00:44:22.744
non-fusion cancers in the middle, we saw another gene emerge, which

741
00:44:22.804 --> 00:44:25.944
was SMAD6, that suppresses TGF-beta signaling.

742
00:44:26.414 --> 00:44:30.404
And then in fusion driven lung cancers, a gene called IREB2,

743
00:44:30.444 --> 00:44:34.314
which regulates intracellular iron homeostasis and actually lies

744
00:44:34.344 --> 00:44:37.184
within a known lung cancer susceptibility locus.

745
00:44:38.204 --> 00:44:42.064
So when we look to see where these variants actually were in the proteins, they do

746
00:44:42.124 --> 00:44:45.234
cluster in functionally important domains, and it supports their

747
00:44:45.824 --> 00:44:49.424
potential biological relevance and suggests to us that rare

748
00:44:49.464 --> 00:44:53.224
germline variation contributes not only to overall risk, but to

749
00:44:53.304 --> 00:44:56.524
specific pathways and tumor subtypes that develop.

750
00:44:58.624 --> 00:45:02.524
So the last thing we looked at is whether structural variants, so these

751
00:45:02.564 --> 00:45:06.424
are variants greater than 50 base pairs in size, also contribute to risk.

752
00:45:07.124 --> 00:45:10.944
And looking first at the gene set level burden, we

753
00:45:11.004 --> 00:45:14.714
see enrichment of rare loss of function structural variants

754
00:45:15.484 --> 00:45:19.424
in the young onset cases. And we saw this particularly in sets

755
00:45:19.484 --> 00:45:23.414
of genes that were lung expressed and loss of function

756
00:45:23.444 --> 00:45:26.944
intolerant, and those are the ones that are circled with the dashed

757
00:45:26.984 --> 00:45:30.934
lines. We then focused on very large structural variants,

758
00:45:31.324 --> 00:45:35.284
so those greater than one megabase in size, where we did see a clear excess

759
00:45:35.324 --> 00:45:38.784
in young onset cases, particularly with regard to large

760
00:45:38.864 --> 00:45:39.444
deletions.

761
00:45:40.384 --> 00:45:44.264
And then this enrichment we found was most pronounced in patients with

762
00:45:44.284 --> 00:45:48.144
fusion driven tumors, where large rare structural

763
00:45:48.184 --> 00:45:52.064
variants were significantly enriched compared to both controls, which are on the

764
00:45:52.104 --> 00:45:54.204
lower left, and then fusion negative cases

765
00:45:55.144 --> 00:45:55.904
on the lower right.

766
00:45:57.104 --> 00:46:00.724
So we can think about these findings as a multilayered model of risk,

767
00:46:01.304 --> 00:46:05.284
where you have germline variation that operates across rare coding variants,

768
00:46:05.634 --> 00:46:08.184
structural variants, and polygenic risk,

769
00:46:09.044 --> 00:46:12.324
alongside environmental exposures such as air pollution.

770
00:46:12.384 --> 00:46:16.204
And this was something we did not look at in this study but would like to

771
00:46:16.284 --> 00:46:19.964
because we think there's likely a large environmental contribution here, and

772
00:46:19.984 --> 00:46:23.664
there's an interplay between genetics and environment, which is something we really

773
00:46:23.724 --> 00:46:27.544
want to look at in this space, particularly around the propensity for

774
00:46:27.584 --> 00:46:29.944
air pollution to cause inflammation in the lung.

775
00:46:30.724 --> 00:46:34.524
And then exposure-wise, a lot of questions are remaining in terms of how much

776
00:46:34.564 --> 00:46:37.424
exposure, when does it matter, and for how long.

777
00:46:37.484 --> 00:46:41.304
So these are all questions we want to answer in this population with

778
00:46:41.344 --> 00:46:41.984
future study.

779
00:46:42.984 --> 00:46:46.864
But ultimately, all of these things can converge in the lung and influence

780
00:46:46.904 --> 00:46:49.384
oncogene selection and lung cancer subtype.

781
00:46:51.664 --> 00:46:55.244
So given the wide array of treatments available for somatic

782
00:46:55.524 --> 00:46:59.424
genotype-directed therapy, germline genotype rarely impacts treatment in

783
00:46:59.444 --> 00:47:03.104
lung cancer. But this is an example where germline

784
00:47:03.124 --> 00:47:05.884
findings actually had pretty profound therapeutic implications.

785
00:47:05.944 --> 00:47:09.284
So this is a patient with a pathogenic germline variant in

786
00:47:09.324 --> 00:47:12.824
